{"type":"message","id":"94ac8c6d","parentId":"cd7aac80","timestamp":"2026-04-28T05:19:25.266Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I acknowledge receipt of the evening message and the critical failure report: **The cron job failed.**\n\nThis requires immediate attention to maintain operational integrity, as failed scheduled tasks are a primary concern outlined in my directives.\n\n**Plan:**\n1.  Diagnose the failed cron job.\n2.  Attempt to fix the cron job or escalate the necessary fix.\n\nI will start by checking the system's cron job status and reviewing the job logs if possible. I will use the `exec` tool for system diagnostics.\n\nFirst, I will try to check the general cron status.<channel|>"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_6010c34f-cbde-49b0-ad6d-9729aefb3dad","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"crontab -l"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"gemma4:e4b","usage":{"input":20188,"output":137,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":20325,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1777353565265}}
{"type":"message","id":"8e4485ba","parentId":"94ac8c6d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T05:19:25.313Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_6010c34f-cbde-49b0-ad6d-9729aefb3dad","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Edit this file to introduce tasks to be run by cron.\n# \n# Each task to run has to be defined through a single line\n# indicating with different fields when the task will be run\n# and what command to run for the task\n# \n# To define the time you can provide concrete values for\n# minute (m), hour (h), day of month (dom), month (mon),\n# and day of week (dow) or use '*' in these fields (for 'any').\n# \n# Notice that tasks will be started based on the cron's system\n# daemon's notion of time and timezones.\n# \n# Output of the crontab jobs (including errors) is sent through\n# email to the user the crontab file belongs to (unless redirected).\n# \n# For example, you can run a backup of all your user accounts\n# at 5 a.m every week with:\n# 0 5 * * 1 tar -zcf /var/backups/home.tgz /home/\n# \n# For more information see the manual pages of crontab(5) and cron(8)\n# \n# m h  dom mon dow   command\n* * * * * /usr/local/bin/openclaw-tasks/email-listener.sh"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":26,"aggregated":"# Edit this file to introduce tasks to be run by cron.\n# \n# Each task to run has to be defined through a single line\n# indicating with different fields when the task will be run\n# and what command to run for the task\n# \n# To define the time you can provide concrete values for\n# minute (m), hour (h), day of month (dom), month (mon),\n# and day of week (dow) or use '*' in these fields (for 'any').\n# \n# Notice that tasks will be started based on the cron's system\n# daemon's notion of time and timezones.\n# \n# Output of the crontab jobs (including errors) is sent through\n# email to the user the crontab file belongs to (unless redirected).\n# \n# For example, you can run a backup of all your user accounts\n# at 5 a.m every week with:\n# 0 5 * * 1 tar -zcf /var/backups/home.tgz /home/\n# \n# For more information see the manual pages of crontab(5) and cron(8)\n# \n# m h  dom mon dow   command\n* * * * * /usr/local/bin/openclaw-tasks/email-listener.sh","cwd":"/home/dai/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777353565313}}
